---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout title="Delaware Probate FAQs">

<section class="faq-hero">
  <div class="container">
    <h1>Delaware Probate Frequently Asked Questions</h1>

    <p>
      Answers to common questions about probate, inherited property,
      executors, heirs, and estate administration in Delaware.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="faq-content">
  <div class="container">

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h2>How long does probate take in Delaware?</h2>
      <p>
        Every estate is different. Simple estates may be completed in several
        months, while more complex estates can take significantly longer.
        Factors include creditor claims, property issues, taxes, and disputes
        among heirs.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h2>Can I sell an inherited house during probate?</h2>
      <p>
        In many situations, inherited property can be sold during probate,
        but court requirements and executor authority can affect the process.
        Always verify the estate's specific circumstances before proceeding.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h2>Who is responsible for maintaining the property?</h2>
      <p>
        The executor or estate representative is generally responsible for
        protecting estate assets, including real estate, until the estate
        administration process is completed.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h2>What happens if there is no will?</h2>
      <p>
        Delaware intestacy laws determine how assets are distributed when
        someone dies without a valid will. The court appoints an administrator
        to handle the estate.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h2>What options do heirs have with inherited property?</h2>
      <p>
        Depending on the circumstances, heirs may choose to keep the property,
        rent it, occupy it, sell it, or transfer ownership. Each option has
        legal, financial, and tax considerations.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h2>Where can I learn more?</h2>
      <p>
        Visit our Probate Resource Center and download our free Delaware
        Probate Property Guide for additional educational information.
      </p>
    </div>

  </div>
</section>

<style>
  .container {
    width: min(1100px, 92%);
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  .faq-hero {
    background: #eef3f7;
    padding: 80px 0;
  }

  .faq-hero h1 {
    font-size: 3rem;
    color: #12355b;
    margin-bottom: 20px;
  }

  .faq-hero p {
    font-size: 1.2rem;
    max-width: 800px;
  }

  .faq-content {
    padding: 80px 0;
  }

  .faq-item {
    margin-bottom: 50px;
    padding-bottom: 30px;
    border-bottom: 1px solid #dbe3ea;
  }

  .faq-item h2 {
    color: #12355b;
    margin-bottom: 15px;
  }

  .faq-item p {
    line-height: 1.8;
    font-size: 1.05rem;
  }
</style>

</BaseLayout>